Here's how to implement all three in your `EditProductPage`:

```csharp
public partial class EditProductPage : ContentPage
{
    private bool _hasUnsavedChanges;

    public EditProductPage()
    {
        InitializeComponent();

        // 3. Custom "Cancel" back button
        Shell.SetBackButtonBehavior(this, new BackButtonBehavior
        {
            TextOverride = "Cancel",
            Command = new Command(async () => await TryGoBack())
        });
    }

    // 1 & 2. Intercept hardware/swipe back
    protected override bool OnBackButtonPressed()
    {
        if (_hasUnsavedChanges)
        {
            // Fire-and-forget since the override is synchronous
            Dispatcher.Dispatch(async () => await TryGoBack());
            return true; // cancel default navigation
        }
        return false; // allow normal back
    }

    private async Task TryGoBack()
    {
        if (_hasUnsavedChanges)
        {
            bool leave = await DisplayAlert(
                "Unsaved Changes",
                "You have unsaved changes. Discard them?",
                "Discard", "Stay");

            if (!leave) return; // user chose Stay — cancel navigation
        }

        await Shell.Current.GoBackAsync();
    }
}
```

**Key points:**

- **`OnBackButtonPressed`** — handles Android hardware/gesture back. Return `true` to cancel navigation.
- **`BackButtonBehavior`** — replaces the Shell toolbar back arrow with a "Cancel" button whose `Command` routes through the same confirmation logic.
- **iOS swipe-back** — `BackButtonBehavior.Command` disables the swipe gesture automatically. If you need swipe support without the custom button, you'll need a platform-specific handler to intercept it.
